diagnoses.name: Hypertension
diagnoses.reasoning: High blood pressure can exacerbate atherosclerosis and lead to episodes of epistaxis due to increased blood pressure in the nasal vessels. Chronic conditions like hypertension can also contribute to depression.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Often caused by the Epstein-Barr virus, it can lead to lymphadenitis, and the general malaise associated can contribute to symptoms of depression. Although indirectly related, the stress on the body can exacerbate blepharospasm due to fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.reasoning: This autoimmune disease can cause a wide range of symptoms, including lymphadenitis and depression. It can also be associated with atherosclerosis as part of its cardiovascular effects.

diagnoses.name: Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis
diagnoses.reasoning: A rare condition characterized by inflammation of the blood vessels, which can lead to symptoms such as epistaxis and contribute to atherosclerosis. The systemic nature of the disease can also impact mental health, causing depression.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.reasoning: HIV can cause lymphadenitis as part of its initial symptoms. Over time, the progression to AIDS can exacerbate mental health issues like depression. Additionally, patients with HIV/AIDS may experience a higher risk of atherosclerosis due to the virus itself and antiretroviral therapy.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.reasoning: While primarily a psychiatric diagnosis, anxiety can manifest physically in ways that exacerbate other conditions. The stress from anxiety can lead to hypertension, worsening atherosclerosis, and epistaxis. Physical symptoms of anxiety may include muscle tension leading to blepharospasm.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.reasoning: Some forms of leukemia can cause lymphadenitis due to the proliferation of leukocytes. The systemic nature of leukemia can cause fatigue and weakness, contributing to depression. Additionally, some treatment regimens can have side effects that include blepharospasm.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.reasoning: An autoimmune disease that primarily affects the joints but can have systemic manifestations including atherosclerosis due to chronic inflammation. Lymphadenitis may occur in more severe cases. Depression is also common in chronic diseases like rheumatoid arthritis.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.reasoning: This condition involves the growth of tiny inflammatory cells in different parts of the body, including the lymph nodes, causing lymphadenitis. It can also affect the eyes, potentially leading to blepharospasm. Patients with sarcoidosis may experience depression due to the chronic nature of the disease.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.reasoning: Chronic metabolic disorder that can lead to atherosclerosis as part of its complication spectrum. Patients with diabetes may experience depression due to the chronic management of the condition. While not directly causing epistaxis or blepharospasm, the overall stress and complications of diabetes can contribute to a wide range of symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition where the kidneys don't work as well as they should. It can lead to symptoms such as nausea and non-restorative sleep due to toxin build-up in the body.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An immune system disorder characterized by dry eyes and dry mouth, which can lead to eye irritation. Patients may also experience fatigue, which can affect sleep quality.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can cause widespread inflammation and tissue damage in affected organs including the kidneys (leading to chronic kidney disease), the skin, joints, and other organs, accounting for hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by widespread pain and fatigue. It can lead to non-restorative sleep and heightened sensitivity to stimuli, potentially explaining hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Diabetic Nephropathy
diagnoses.description: A type of chronic kidney disease caused by diabetes. It can lead to symptoms such as nausea. The connection between diabetes and its control can also affect sleep patterns and potentially eye health.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by extreme fatigue or tiredness that doesn't improve with rest and can worsen with physical or mental activity, it might account for non-restorative sleep.

diagnoses.name: Uveitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the middle layer of the eye, leading to irritated eyes. It is associated with autoimmune disorders, which can sometimes also affect the kidneys.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Hepatitis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that targets the liver, leading to chronic inflammation. It can present with fatigue and nausea, and its systemic nature might indirectly affect sleep and eye health.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder characterized by chronic inflammation of joints, which can lead to systemic symptoms including chronic fatigue, affecting sleep, and Sjögren's syndrome, potentially explaining the irritated eyes.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition where the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormones, leading to symptoms such as fatigue, which can impact sleep quality, and a general slowing down of bodily functions, which can include reducing kidney function over time.

diagnoses.description: Hemochromatosis

diagnoses.description: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.rationale: Hypoglycemia is a direct symptom of diabetes, especially in patients receiving insulin or other medications. Atherosclerosis is a common complication. Diabetes can also lead to infertility.

diagnoses.description: Antiphospholipid Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: This syndrome can lead to atherosclerosis and is associated with infertility. Hypoferritinemia and epistaxis might be associated due to general bleeding and clotting disturbances.

diagnoses.description: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.rationale: Directly linked to infertility. Can also lead to insulin resistance, a cause of hypoglycemia, and is associated with a higher risk of developing atherosclerosis.

diagnoses.description: Chronic Liver Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Can lead to hypoglycemia due to impaired glycogen storage. Atherosclerosis could be related to associated metabolic disorders. Infertility and epistaxis may also be symptoms due to hormonal imbalances and increased bleeding tendency.

diagnoses.description: Thrombotic Thrombocytopenic Purpura (TTP)
diagnoses.rationale: Though fitting less precisely, epistaxis could be a symptom due to the small blood clots reducing blood flow. Other symptoms might overlap with complications or secondary issues.

diagnoses.description: Cushing's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Might cause infertility, hypoglycemia (though hyperglycemia is more common), and atherosclerosis due to metabolic disturbances including elevated cortisol levels.

diagnoses.description: Von Willebrand Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Primarily explains epistaxis due to clotting factor issues. While not directly explaining other symptoms, complications or associated conditions could overlap.

diagnoses.description: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.rationale: Directly associated with hypoferritinemia. While not directly causing the other symptoms, complications or coexisting conditions may lead to a similar symptom complex.

diagnoses.description: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.rationale: Can lead to infertility and, in some cases, hypoglycemia. Atherosclerosis might also be a complication due to elevated cholesterol in prolonged untreated cases.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues. It can explain hypermobility, potentially contribute to postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome (POTS), and cause diffuse pain including muscle pain.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues. It may also be associated with symptoms like POTS.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium which is spread by ticks. It can cause diverse symptoms including muscle pain, lymphadenopathy, and potentially contribute to autonomic disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (Myalgic Encephalomyelitis)
diagnoses.description: A complex chronic condition characterized by extreme fatigue, pain, and dizziness including POTS. It may also include symptoms such as lymphadenopathy and muscle pain.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease where the immune system attacks its own tissues, causing widespread inflammation and tissue damage in the affected organs. Can manifest with lymphadenopathy, musculoskeletal pain, and potentially vascular symptoms affecting heart rate.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that attacks the glands that provide lubrication to the eyes and mouth. It also can cause widespread systemic symptoms including muscle pain and fatigue, which might contribute to POTS-related symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease of the central nervous system that can lead to fatigue, pain, and autonomic symptoms. While not commonly directly related to POTS, it can cause a wide variety of symptoms including those affecting muscle strength and coordination.

diagnoses.name: Small Fiber Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A condition affecting the small fibers of the nervous system. It can cause symptoms like pain, autonomic dysfunction including POTS, and potentially could be linked with conditions leading to lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that may present with features of multiple other connective tissue diseases, such as lupus and Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome. Symptoms can include muscle pain, hypermobility, and autonomic dysregulation.

diagnoses.name: Mast Cell Activation Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition where mast cells incorrectly release too many chemical mediators, leading to a wide range of symptoms including tachycardia, potentially POTS, pain, and inflammation that might explain lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms including severe headaches, nausea, light sensitivity, and weakness. Aura symptoms like paresthesia can also occur before the headache.

diagnoses.name: Tension-Type Headache
diagnoses.description: A common type of headache characterized by mild to moderate pain, often described as feeling like a tight band around the head. Nausea and photophobia can occur but are less common.

diagnoses.name: Cluster Headache
diagnoses.description: A condition that produces severe headaches on one side of the head. It can be accompanied by nausea, photophobia, and weakness. Paresthesia is not typical but can occur in association with other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An infection of the protective membranes covering the brain and spinal cord, known as the meninges. It can lead to severe headache, nausea, weakness, and sensitivity to light. Paresthesia is less common but can happen due to nerve involvement.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. Symptoms can vary widely and include fatigue, weakness, headache, photophobia, and paresthesia.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition that occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Symptoms can include headache, nausea, weakness, and paresthesia.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain. Symptoms may include headache, nausea, weakness, paresthesia, and photophobia, depending on the tumor's location and size.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder in which the body's immune system attacks the nerves. Weakness and tingling in the extremities are its first symptoms. Nausea, photophobia, and headache can also occur as the disorder progresses.

diagnoses.name: Subarachnoid Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: Bleeding in the space between the brain and the tissue covering the brain, a serious condition. Symptoms include sudden severe headache, nausea, photophobia, weakness, and sometimes paresthesia if nerve pathways are affected.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacterium spread by ticks. Symptoms can include headache, nausea, weakness, photophobia, and paresthesia in the limbs as the disease progresses.
